SN  - 0304-4076
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-4076(90)90065-2
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0304407690900652
AB  - In this paper we explore the following fundamental question: Are there reasonable conditions under which the parameters of estimated aggregate demand systems will uniquely identify underlying individual demand systems? In the process of examining this question we show that the conditions which have been reported in the literature are incomplete. The exercise is carried out in the framework of individual demand systems which are integrable and exactly aggregable.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Coherency of the indirect translog demand system with binding nonnegativity constraints
AU  - Van Soest, Arthur
AU  - Kooreman, Peter
JO  - Journal of Econometrics
VL  - 44
IS  - 3
SP  - 391
EP  - 400
PY  - 1990
DA  - 1990/06/01/
SN  - 0304-4076
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-4076(90)90066-3
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0304407690900663
AB  - We study the incoherency problem of the indirect translog demand system in which nonnegativity constraints on all goods are explicitly taken into account. Two examples illustrate the nature of the problem: The set of constraints which are binding is not always uniquely defined, and thus the model may not have a reduced form. We derive sufficient conditions for coherency which are related to regularity properties of the demand system; these conditions appear to be ‘almost necessary’ for regularity.
